---
description: Avoid excessive blank lines in TypeScript files; always use braces for control flow
globs: "**/*.ts"
alwaysApply: false
---

# Whitespace / Blank Line Rules

- Do not add blank lines between sequential statements within the same logical block (inside a try, for, if, etc.)
- One blank line is acceptable between top-level method definitions and between distinct logical sections
- Never pad the inside of control flow blocks (for, if, try) with leading/trailing blank lines

```typescript
// BAD
for (const item of items) {
   if (this.isShuttingDown) break;

   const result = await this.process(item);
   processed += result.count;

}

// GOOD
for (const item of items) {
   if (this.isShuttingDown) { break; }
   const result = await this.process(item);
   processed += result.count;
}
```

# Always Use Braces for Control Flow

Never write braceless single-line control flow. Always wrap the body in braces, even for a single statement. Braceless forms are easy to misread and error-prone when lines are added later.

```typescript
// BAD
if (this.isShuttingDown) break;
if (!account) return null;
for (const x of items) doSomething(x);

// GOOD
if (this.isShuttingDown) { break; }
if (!account) { return null; }
for (const x of items) { doSomething(x); }
```

This applies to `if`, `else`, `for`, `while`, `do`, and any other control flow construct.
